        theme: "Power of Nature vs. Human Structures",
        analysis: `"Tissue" explores the tension between the permanence that human beings seek through their constructions and the impermanence that is the fundamental condition of nature and human life. Throughout the poem, Dharker presents various examples of human structures — holy books, maps, architects' plans, financial records — all of which are rendered on paper, a material that is inherently fragile and temporary. By choosing paper as her central metaphor, Dharker emphasises that all human constructs, no matter how significant they may seem, are ultimately impermanent.

The poem imagines 'an architect' who could 'use the paper to design / a building so the daylight could be / altered by it.' This visionary image suggests an alternative relationship with the material world — one in which structures are not designed to dominate and endure but to interact with natural light, to be permeable and responsive to the natural environment. The repeated references to 'light' throughout the poem reinforce this idea: light represents the natural, the spiritual, and the transcendent, while paper and buildings represent human attempts to contain and control.

The final image of the poem — 'turned into your skin' — completes this theme by suggesting that the human body itself is the ultimate example of the tension between structure and impermanence. Skin is a living tissue that provides structure and protection, yet it is thin, fragile, and constantly changing. Unlike the rigid structures of buildings and borders, skin is organic, flexible, and mortal. Dharker suggests that we should model our institutions and attitudes on the qualities of tissue and skin — embracing fragility, transparency, and impermanence rather than seeking to build permanent, rigid structures that deny the fundamental nature of human existence.`
