        analysis: `The theme of fragility and impermanence runs throughout the entire poem, established from the very first image of paper that has been 'thinned by turning.' This image captures the dual nature of fragility — the pages are thinned because they have been handled with love and devotion over many years, suggesting that what is most treasured is also most vulnerable to wear and decay. The light that shines through the thinned paper is beautiful precisely because of the paper's fragility; if the pages were thick and opaque, the light could not penetrate them.

Dharker extends this idea to all forms of human construction. The 'borderlines' on maps can be redrawn, financial 'records' can be erased, and even buildings — the most solid and permanent of human structures — could, in Dharker's imagination, be made of paper that 'lets the daylight through.' The poem consistently challenges the human desire for permanence and durability, suggesting that there is beauty and wisdom in embracing impermanence.

The word 'tissue' itself is carefully chosen for its multiple meanings. It refers to tissue paper (thin, translucent, fragile), to the tissue of the human body (organic, living, mortal), and to the broader 'tissue' of human society (the interconnected web of relationships, institutions, and structures that constitute civilisation). All of these are fragile and impermanent, yet all are essential and beautiful. The poem's message is not nihilistic — it does not suggest that because things are impermanent they are meaningless. Rather, it suggests that impermanence should be embraced and celebrated, that the fragility of paper, skin, and human life is what makes them precious.`
