    languageAnalysis: `Dharker's language in "Tissue" is characteristically precise, layered, and rich in multiple meanings. The central conceit of the poem — the extended metaphor of paper/tissue — allows her to explore a wide range of ideas through a single, flexible image. The word 'tissue' itself operates on multiple levels: tissue paper (thin, translucent, disposable), body tissue (organic, living, mortal), and the metaphorical 'tissue' of society (the interconnected web of relationships and structures). This polysemy gives the poem a remarkable depth and coherence.

The language is predominantly concrete and sensory. Dharker describes paper that is 'smoothed and stroked and thinned,' 'fine slips from grocery stores,' and 'the hand of the builder.' These tactile, visual details ground the poem's abstract ideas in physical reality, making them accessible and vivid. The repeated emphasis on light — 'light,' 'daylight,' 'sun shines through,' 'transparent' — creates a luminous quality that pervades the entire poem, associating transparency and permeability with positivity and spiritual illumination.

Dharker makes effective use of listing and cataloguing. The various forms of paper — Koran pages, maps, receipts, architects' plans — are presented in a cumulative sequence that builds the poem's argument about the ubiquity and fragility of paper records. Each new example extends the metaphor, demonstrating that paper pervades every aspect of human life, from the sacred to the mundane.

The tone of the poem is meditative and contemplative, created through long, flowing sentences that span multiple stanzas and the frequent use of enjambment. The conditional mood — 'if buildings were paper,' 'might fly our lives' — gives the poem a speculative, visionary quality, as though Dharker is not describing the world as it is but imagining how it might be. This speculative tone avoids didacticism, inviting the reader to consider possibilities rather than accept instructions.

The final shift from 'paper' to 'your skin' is linguistically significant. Throughout the poem, the language has been relatively impersonal and abstract, discussing paper in general terms. The sudden introduction of the second-person pronoun 'your' in the final line creates an intimate, direct connection between poet and reader, transforming the poem from a philosophical meditation into a personal address. This linguistic shift mirrors the thematic shift from abstract structures to the human body, grounding the poem's ideas in the most immediate and personal reality of all — the reader's own physical existence.`,
    structureAnalysis: `"Tissue" has a highly distinctive and unusual structure that is integral to its meaning. The poem consists of ten stanzas, nine of which are quatrains (four lines each), followed by a single isolated line that forms the tenth 'stanza.' This final isolated line — 'turned into your skin' — stands apart from the rest of the poem both visually and thematically, creating a dramatic structural emphasis that underscores the poem's central revelation: that all the paper structures discussed in the poem are ultimately metaphors for human skin and human mortality.

The poem's stanzas are not self-contained units of meaning; instead, sentences and clauses run freely across stanza breaks through extensive enjambment. This creates a flowing, continuous movement that mirrors the poem's argument about the interconnectedness of all things — sacred texts, maps, receipts, buildings, and skin are all linked in one continuous chain of association. The enjambment also creates a sense of lightness and weightlessness that reflects the poem's celebration of fragility and transparency.

There is no regular rhyme scheme or metre, which gives the poem a conversational, meditative quality that suits its reflective, philosophical content. The free verse form also reflects the poem's thematic content — just as the poem argues against rigid structures and fixed boundaries, its form refuses to be constrained by regular metre or rhyme. However, Dharker does use internal echoes and repetitions — particularly the word 'paper' and images of light — to create coherence and unity across the poem's ten stanzas.

The poem builds through accumulation, adding layer upon layer of paper imagery. Each stanza introduces a new form of paper or a new way of thinking about paper, and the cumulative effect is to create a rich, complex tapestry of associations. The structure therefore mirrors the 'tissue' of the title — each stanza is a thin layer that, when combined with the others, creates something substantial and meaningful.

The progression from sacred text to maps to receipts to buildings to skin creates a movement from the abstract and institutional to the personal and physical, culminating in the final line's dramatic focus on the reader's own body. This structural progression reinforces the poem's argument that the most important reality is not found in grand structures or institutions but in the fragile, mortal human body.`,
