        analysis: `Resistance runs through "Checking Out Me History" at every level — in its content, its language, its form, and its tone. The poem is itself an act of resistance against the cultural hegemony of the British education system. By writing about the histories that the system excludes, Agard challenges its authority and exposes its biases. By writing in Caribbean Creole rather than standard English, he rejects the linguistic norms of the coloniser and asserts the validity of his own language and culture.

The historical figures celebrated in the poem are all exemplars of resistance. Toussaint L'Ouverture resisted the French colonial system and led the only successful slave revolt in history. Nanny de Maroon resisted British colonial forces in Jamaica through guerrilla warfare. Mary Seacole resisted the racism of the British War Office by travelling to Crimea at her own expense. These figures are presented not merely as historical curiosities but as role models and sources of inspiration for contemporary resistance against ongoing forms of cultural and political oppression.

The poem's performative, spoken-word style is also a form of resistance. The rhythmic, repetitive structure draws on Caribbean oral traditions — calypso, reggae, and storytelling — rather than the literary conventions of the English poetic tradition. By performing the poem in this way, Agard challenges the idea that poetry must conform to European forms and conventions, demonstrating that Caribbean oral traditions are equally valid and powerful modes of artistic expression. The poem thus practices what it preaches: it does not merely argue for the inclusion of diverse voices and histories; it embodies that diversity in its own form and language.`
